          "body": "The oracle closes with three divine declarations that represent one of the most theologically charged sentences in the entire Old Testament: 'Blessed is Egypt My people, and Assyria the work of My hands, and Israel My inheritance.' Three nations, three distinct covenant identities, one divine speaker. 'My people' (am) is the Exodus covenant term for Israel (Exodus 6:7; Leviticus 26:12). 'The work of My hands' (maaseh yadav) is the Creator's proprietary language for His creatures (Psalm 138:8; Isaiah 60:21). 'My inheritance' (nachalah) is the term for Israel's covenant possession of the land. Isaiah applies all three terms simultaneously to three different nations — the world's two superpowers and the covenant nation. Egypt receives the most intimate covenant title: 'My people.' This does not abrogate Israel's election; it expands it. The Abrahamic promise ('in you all the families of the earth will be blessed,' Genesis 12:3) reaches its most dramatic pre-New Testament expression in this verse. The nation Israel most tempted to trust and the nation Israel most tempted to fear both end at the same table, sharing covenant identities with the nation Yahweh chose as His own."
